<p class="eyebrow">Software-defined networking</p>
<h1>A small appliance for difficult SIP networks.</h1>
<p class="lede">The VoiceTel SDN appliance sits inside the customer LAN and establishes a secure tunnel to VoiceTel, helping PBX registrations and media flows avoid common NAT, ALG, UDP timer, and firewall problems.</p>
<p class="hero-actions">
	<a class="btn btn-primary" href="/contact/">Request access</a>
	<a class="btn btn-secondary" href="http://sdn.voicetel.com">Technical specification</a>
</p>

<section class="section-block" data-section-type="problem-solution">
	<h2>What it solves</h2>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>No audio or one-way audio</strong> — Media-path issues often come from NAT, firewall, or RTP pinhole behavior. The appliance gives VoiceTel a controlled path.</li>
		<li><strong>Registration instability</strong> — Keep local PBX registration behavior stable while the appliance handles the upstream secure path.</li>
		<li><strong>Firewall policy friction</strong> — Reduce the need to open broad inbound SIP and RTP exposure at the customer edge.</li>
		<li><strong>Support visibility</strong> — Give support a clearer demarcation point for diagnosing LAN, tunnel, SIP, and media behavior.</li>
	</ul>
</section>

<section class="section-block" data-section-type="compatibility">
	<h2>Integrations</h2>
	<p>Position native integrations with Asterisk, FreePBX, FreeSWITCH, and FusionPBX only after installation guides are present in docs.</p>
</section>

<aside class="caveat-block">
	<h3>Deployment caveat</h3>
	<p>Do not claim the appliance fixes every network issue. Some LAN, QoS, ISP, or device problems still require normal network engineering.</p>
</aside>
